# AI Token Budgeter — Engineering Standards

Read PLAN.md for MVP scope and ARCHITECTURE.md for design rationale.

---

## Language & Stack

- Go 1.22+ for the data plane proxy
- Redis 7+ for budget state (via `go-redis`)
- Lua scripts for all Redis mutations — no exceptions
- `net/http/httputil` for reverse proxy base; custom `ResponseWriter`/`io.Reader` tap for stream inspection

---

## Budget Atomicity (Non-Negotiable)

- NEVER use plain Redis GET/DECR from application code. All budget mutations MUST go through Lua scripts.
- MUST implement two scripts: `reserve_budget` (pre-request) and `settle_budget` (post-response). Do NOT combine into a single check-then-blind-decrement flow.
- Pre-request check MUST atomically reserve `estimated_cost`, not merely verify `balance > 0`.
- Settlement MUST be idempotent on `request_id`. Duplicate calls return existing state, never double-adjust.
- Load Lua scripts with `SCRIPT LOAD` at startup; use `EVALSHA` in the hot path.

---

## Fail-Open Policy (Non-Negotiable)

- If Redis is unreachable OR pre-check times out (>50ms): MUST forward request to provider. NEVER return an error to the client due to enforcement infrastructure failure.
- Increment `fail_open_total` metric on every fail-open bypass.
- Fire Slack CRITICAL alert on fail-open events (Day 2+, not Day 3).
- `/readyz` returns 503 when Redis unreachable (for orchestration). The proxy process MUST still serve LLM traffic fail-open.
- Budget exhausted in `enforce` mode: return **429** with `Retry-After` and JSON error body. Do NOT forward to provider.
- Do NOT use HTTP 402. Clients rarely handle it.
- Default `ENFORCEMENT_MODE=shadow` until explicitly promoted to `enforce`.

### Enforcement Modes

| Mode | Pre-check | Settlement | Block on exhausted? |
|------|-----------|------------|---------------------|
| `off` | Skip | Skip | No |
| `shadow` | Run + log | Run + log | No |
| `enforce` | Run | Run | Yes (429) |

---

## Connection Pooling

- HTTP upstream: configure `http.Transport` with `MaxIdleConns`, `MaxIdleConnsPerHost`, `IdleConnTimeout`.
- Redis: configure `go-redis` with `PoolSize` >= 10, `MinIdleConns` >= 10, command timeout 50ms.
- Both pools are required. HTTP pooling alone is insufficient.

---

## Header Handling

- Forward method, path, query string, and body unchanged.
- MUST rewrite `Host` to the provider hostname.
- MUST strip hop-by-hop headers: `Connection`, `Keep-Alive`, `Transfer-Encoding`, `Upgrade`, `TE`, `Trailer`.
- MUST NOT forward internal headers upstream: `X-Budget-Bucket-Id`, `X-Request-Id` (unless provider expects it).
- MUST NOT log `Authorization` headers.
- Bucket identity comes from trusted source (gateway injection or mTLS). Do NOT trust client-supplied bucket headers in production.

---

## Stream Handling Constraints

- MUST NOT buffer the full response body for streaming requests. Tee bytes to client as they arrive.
- SSE parser MUST be a proper state machine handling comments, blank lines, and interleaved events.
- Provider-specific usage extractors MUST sit behind a Go interface (`UsageExtractor`).
- MUST support both streaming (SSE) and non-streaming (JSON body) response paths.
- On client disconnect (`Context.Done()` or write error): settle at reserved amount if usage not yet received.
- On missing usage metadata: settle at reserved amount (worst-case). Log `usage_missing_total`. Do NOT block the user response.
- On provider 4xx/5xx: release reservation (full refund of hold).
- If `Content-Encoding: gzip`: decompress for usage tap only; pass original encoding to client.
- Goroutine lifecycle: SSE tap MUST NOT leak goroutines on client disconnect. Verify with load test (1000 aborted streams).

---

## Idempotency

- Every request MUST have a `request_id` from `X-Request-Id` header or a generated UUID.
- Lua `reserve_budget` MUST detect duplicate `request_id` and return existing reservation.
- Lua `settle_budget` MUST detect already-settled or expired reservations and return OK.

---

## Reservation TTL

- Unsettled reservations MUST have Redis key TTL (`RESERVATION_TTL`, default 5m).
- TTL auto-releases holds on proxy crash or settlement failure.
- Settlement failures: retry 3x with backoff, then rely on TTL expiry.

---

## Performance Targets

- p99 pre-check overhead: <5ms (excludes provider RTT).
- Stream passthrough: zero additional buffering latency.
- Async settlement adds zero user-facing latency.

---

## Observability (Required Metrics)

Implement these from Day 2:

- `budget_check_total{result}` — counter: allowed / denied / fail_open
- `budget_reserve_duration_seconds` — histogram
- `budget_settle_total{result}` — counter: success / retry / missing_usage
- `fail_open_total` — counter
- `reservation_unsettled` — gauge

Structured JSON log per request: `{request_id, bucket_id, reserved, actual, mode, outcome}`.

---

## Security

- Bucket ID must not be client-spoofable in production.
- Do not log secrets (`Authorization`, API keys).
- Rate-limit proxy admin endpoints (`/healthz`, `/readyz`).

---

## Testing Standards

- Unit tests for Lua scripts using `miniredis`.
- Integration test: proxy forwards to mock upstream (Day 1).
- Integration test: N concurrent requests cannot overspend bucket (Day 3).
- Recorded SSE fixtures per provider for parser tests (OpenAI + Anthropic).
- Load test: no goroutine leaks on 1000 aborted streams.

---

## Code Style

- Match existing Go conventions in the repo. Keep packages focused: `proxy`, `budget`, `usage`, `config`.
- Minimize scope — no abstractions beyond what the MVP requires.
- Comments only for non-obvious business logic (reservation/settlement lifecycle, fail-open rationale).
- No over-engineering: two Lua scripts, one interface for usage extractors, one config struct.

---

## Day 2 Scope (Redis Budget Engine)

- Budget unit: raw token count (integer in Redis).
- Parse `max_tokens` from request JSON; estimate = max_tokens + PROMPT_TOKEN_BUFFER; fallback DEFAULT_RESERVATION_ESTIMATE.
- Wire `RedisBudgetChecker` into existing `BudgetChecker` interface — do NOT rewrite enforcement mode logic.
- Day 2 wires: `reserve_budget` (pre-request), `release_budget` (upstream 4xx/5xx in ModifyResponse).
- Day 2 does NOT wire: `settle_budget` on 200 responses (Day 3 — usage parsing).
- Generate UUID for `X-Request-Id` when absent.
- Empty `X-Budget-Bucket-Id`: fail-open in shadow/enforce (cannot enforce without bucket).
- Request body must be read-and-restored so upstream receives full payload after estimate parse.
- Implement `release_budget` Lua script in addition to reserve/settle.

---

## Day 3 Scope (Usage Extraction & Hardening)

### Build Order (strict — one phase per PR/commit)

1. **Phase A:** non-streaming JSON settle only
2. **Phase B:** SSE streaming settle only (after Phase A tests pass)
3. **Phase C:** disconnect, missing usage, retry, E2E, goroutine test (after Phase B tests pass)

Do NOT implement all phases in one changeset.

### TDD Requirements

- Write failing unit test first for each new function (extractor, parser, body wrap).
- Run `go test ./...` after each phase before proceeding.
- All existing Day 1 + Day 2 tests MUST continue to pass — never delete or weaken them.

### Provider Scope

- OpenAI only for Day 3. Do NOT implement Anthropic extractors.
- `actual = usage.total_tokens` (raw token count).

### Settlement Wiring

- Add `BudgetSettler` interface; implement via existing `*budget.Client.Settle`.
- Store `reserved` amount in request context after pre-check (for disconnect/missing-usage fallback).
- Non-streaming: sync `Settle` on body `Close()`.
- Streaming: async `go Settle(...)` after final chunk; use `sync.Once` to prevent double-settle.
- Do NOT change Lua scripts.

### Stream Constraints

- MUST NOT buffer full SSE response body.
- SSE parser MUST handle partial lines across `Read()` calls.
- On missing usage or client disconnect: `Settle(requestID, reserved)`.
- Settlement retry: 3x backoff; log error if all fail (TTL is safety net).

### Code Quality

- Match existing package layout and naming in `internal/budget` and `internal/proxy`.
- Keep files focused: one body wrap per file (`settling_reader.go`, `stream_tap.go`).
- No new external dependencies beyond what is already in go.mod unless strictly necessary.
- Comments only for non-obvious logic (sync.Once settle guard, partial SSE line buffering).
- Minimize handler.go growth — extract body wraps to separate files.

---

## Post-MVP Launch Scope (v1 Self-Hosted)

### GTM & Storage (locked)

- Self-hosted only for v1. No user database. Redis only for budget state.
- One `UPSTREAM_URL` per proxy instance (OpenAI OR Anthropic).

### Build Order (strict — one phase per changeset)

1. **Launch-1a:** Anthropic JSON extractor + estimate + integration test
2. **Launch-1b:** Anthropic SSE extractor + integration test
3. **Launch-2a:** Admin API + set_budget.lua + tests
4. **Launch-2b:** Docker Compose + Dockerfile + .env.example
5. **Launch-3:** README, RUNBOOK, ONBOARDING, LICENSE

Run `go test ./...` after each phase. Do NOT combine Launch-1 and Launch-2.

### Anthropic Usage

- Non-streaming: actual = usage.input_tokens + usage.output_tokens
- Streaming: parse message_stop (preferred) or accumulate message_delta
- Reuse sse/parser.go; add anthropic_stream.go

### Admin API

- Routes under /admin/v1/buckets/{id} — NOT proxied upstream
- Auth: Bearer ADMIN_API_KEY (required)
- Use set_budget.lua for PUT/topup (Lua-only Redis mutations)
- Rate-limit admin endpoints

### TDD & Quality

- Write failing tests first for each extractor and admin handler
- All existing tests MUST pass — no regressions
- Match existing code style; new packages: internal/admin, extend internal/usage
- No Postgres, no user auth, no billing, no dashboard in this scope

### Documentation

- Update README when Launch-2b ships
- ONBOARDING.md = client setup; docs/RUNBOOK.md = ops

---

## Hosted Product v1 Scope (Multi-Tenant Lean)

### Locked decisions

- You host ONE multi-tenant instance. Customers get `tg_` API keys after Stripe payment.
- Redis = hot budgets only. Postgres = orgs, api_keys, usage_events, Stripe, Slack webhook.
- Auth header for TokenGuard: `X-TokenGuard-Key` (do NOT overload OpenAI Bearer).
- Redis budget key: `budget:{org_id}:{bucket_id}`.
- No React dashboard. Minimal `/ops` HTML page only.
- Pricing: Trial / Indie $15 / Team $39.
- Provider keys: passthrough only — never store.

### Build order (strict — one phase per changeset)

1. **H1:** usage_events on settle/release + dump APIs
2. **H2:** Postgres orgs/api_keys + auth middleware
3. **H3:** per-org Slack + 80% warning
4. **H4:** Stripe Checkout + webhook
5. **H5:** `/ops` HTML page
6. **H6:** compose postgres + VPS deploy docs

Run `go test ./...` after each phase. Do NOT combine phases.

### TDD & quality

- Failing tests first for auth, usage log, Stripe webhook handlers, dump APIs.
- All existing Day 1–3 + Launch tests MUST pass.
- New packages: `internal/store` (Postgres), `internal/billing` (Stripe), extend `internal/admin` and `internal/proxy`.
- No Gemini/Grok native extractors, no SPA, no email in this scope.

### Out of scope (Post-v1)

Gemini, OpenAI-compatible picker UI, self-serve signup polish, React dashboard, Slack buttons, email, SSO.

---

## S1 Self-Serve Onboarding (branch self-serve)

- Implement entire S1 in one changeset per PLAN.md **S1 — Self-Serve Onboarding**.
- Public `/signup`, `/signup/checkout`, `/setup` — no ADMIN_API_KEY.
- Webhook provisions org + tg_ key + default bucket + Redis seed + one-time setup secret.
- Wire default bucket when X-Budget-Bucket-Id missing.
- No React. No email sending. No Gemini.
- TDD; all existing tests must pass; go test ./... green at end.

---

## A1 Customer Analytics (branch analytics)

- Implement entire A1 in one changeset per PLAN.md **A1 — Customer Analytics**.
- Customer-scoped `GET /me/buckets`, `GET /me/usage`, `GET /me/org`, `PATCH /me/slack` auth via `X-TokenGuard-Key`.
- Minimal `/account` HTML (Go templates) — balances + recent usage + Slack update; no React SPA.
- Org isolation mandatory — never leak cross-tenant data.
- Do NOT implement multi-provider routing, Gemini, customer topup, or key remint in A1.
- Operator `/ops` + admin APIs stay ADMIN_API_KEY-only.
- TDD; all existing tests must pass; go test ./... green at end.

---

## M1 Multi-Provider Routing (branch multi-routing)

- Implement entire M1 in one changeset per PLAN.md **M1 — Multi-Provider Routing** and ARCHITECTURE.md **§17**.
- Path prefixes: `/openai/*` → OpenAI upstream + OpenAI extractors; `/anthropic/*` → Anthropic upstream + Anthropic extractors.
- Strip provider prefix before forward; per-request upstream + extractors on context (Director + settle).
- Keep legacy unprefixed paths on `UPSTREAM_URL` / `UPSTREAM_HOST` (backward compatible).
- Same org/bucket budgets for both providers; do not add per-provider wallets.
- Do NOT implement Gemini, Grok, body sniffing, or React dashboard.
- Do not break `/admin`, `/me`, `/account`, `/ops`, `/signup`, `/setup`, `/billing`, health routes.
- TDD; all existing tests must pass; go test ./... green at end.
